shifting historical backdrop, Alan Mintz presents a multilayered history of the town, along with insight into Agnon's fictional transformations. Mintz relates these narrative strategies to catastrophe literature from earlier periods of Jewish history, showing how Agnon's Buczacz is a literary achievement at once innovative in its form of remembrance and deeply rooted in Jewish tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aJews in literature. 4aGalicia. 4aHebrew literature. 4aIsraeli literature. 4aJewish-Polish relations. 4aJews in the Austro-Hungarian Empire. 4aS. Y. Agnon. 4amodern Jewish literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503601864zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601864.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles